 7 Matrix Algebra in R 7.1 Creating a Matrix Use matrix(data, nrow, ncol, byrow) to create a matrix. By default, R fills the matrix column by column; set byrow = TRUE to fill row by row: # Fill by column (default) A &lt;- matrix(c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6), nrow = 2, ncol = 3) A ## [,1] [,2] [,3] ## [1,] 1 3 5 ## [2,] 2 4 6 # Fill by row B &lt;- matrix(c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6), nrow = 2, ncol = 3, byrow = TRUE) B ## [,1] [,2] [,3] ## [1,] 1 2 3 ## [2,] 4 5 6 7.2 Matrix Dimensions M &lt;- matrix(1:12, nrow = 4, ncol = 3) M ## [,1] [,2] [,3] ## [1,] 1 5 9 ## [2,] 2 6 10 ## [3,] 3 7 11 ## [4,] 4 8 12 nrow(M) # Number of rows: 4 ## [1] 4 ncol(M) # Number of columns: 3 ## [1] 3 dim(M) # Dimensions: c(4, 3) ## [1] 4 3 7.3 Special Matrices # Identity diag(3) # 3x3 identity matrix ## [,1] [,2] [,3] ## [1,] 1 0 0 ## [2,] 0 1 0 ## [3,] 0 0 1 # Matrix of zeros matrix(0, nrow = 3, ncol = 3) ## [,1] [,2] [,3] ## [1,] 0 0 0 ## [2,] 0 0 0 ## [3,] 0 0 0 # Matrix of ones matrix(1, nrow = 2, ncol = 4) ## [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4] ## [1,] 1 1 1 1 ## [2,] 1 1 1 1 # Diagonal matrix from a vector diag(c(2, 5, 8)) ## [,1] [,2] [,3] ## [1,] 2 0 0 ## [2,] 0 5 0 ## [3,] 0 0 8 7.4 Indexing and Slicing Matrix elements are accessed using [row, col]. Leaving a dimension blank selects all rows or columns: M &lt;- matrix(1:9, nrow = 3, ncol = 3, byrow = TRUE) M ## [,1] [,2] [,3] ## [1,] 1 2 3 ## [2,] 4 5 6 ## [3,] 7 8 9 M[2, 3] # Element at row 2, column 3 ## [1] 6 M[1, ] # Entire first row ## [1] 1 2 3 M[, 2] # Entire second column ## [1] 2 5 8 M[1:2, 2:3] # Submatrix: rows 1-2, columns 2-3 ## [,1] [,2] ## [1,] 2 3 ## [2,] 5 6 7.5 Matrix Addition and Subtraction Matrices must have the same dimensions for addition and subtraction: A &lt;- matrix(c(1, 2, 3, 4), nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE) B &lt;- matrix(c(5, 6, 7, 8), nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE) A + B # Matrix addition ## [,1] [,2] ## [1,] 6 8 ## [2,] 10 12 A - B # Matrix subtraction ## [,1] [,2] ## [1,] -4 -4 ## [2,] -4 -4 7.6 Scalar Multiplication A &lt;- matrix(c(1, 2, 3, 4), nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE) 3 * A # Multiply every element by 3 ## [,1] [,2] ## [1,] 3 6 ## [2,] 9 12 7.7 Element-wise Multiplication Use * for element-wise multiplication: A &lt;- matrix(c(1, 2, 3, 4), nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE) B &lt;- matrix(c(5, 6, 7, 8), nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE) A * B # Element-wise (NOT matrix) multiplication ## [,1] [,2] ## [1,] 5 12 ## [2,] 21 32 7.8 Matrix Multiplication Use %*% for true matrix multiplication. Matrices must be conformable: the number of columns in the first matrix must equal the number of rows in the second: A &lt;- matrix(c(1, 2, 3, 4), nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE) # 2x2 B &lt;- matrix(c(5, 6, 7, 8), nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE) # 2x2 A %*% B # Matrix multiplication AB ## [,1] [,2] ## [1,] 19 22 ## [2,] 43 50 # Note: matrix multiplication is NOT commutative B %*% A # BA — generally different from AB ## [,1] [,2] ## [1,] 23 34 ## [2,] 31 46 7.9 Transpose Use t() to transpose a matrix — rows become columns and columns become rows. Mathematically, the transpose of \(A\) is denoted \(A^T\) or \(A&#39;\): A &lt;- matrix(c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6), nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE) A ## [,1] [,2] [,3] ## [1,] 1 2 3 ## [2,] 4 5 6 t(A) # Transpose of A ## [,1] [,2] ## [1,] 1 4 ## [2,] 2 5 ## [3,] 3 6 7.10 Trace of a Matrix The trace is the sum of the diagonal elements. Use sum(diag()): A &lt;- matrix(c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9), nrow = 3, byrow = TRUE) A ## [,1] [,2] [,3] ## [1,] 1 2 3 ## [2,] 4 5 6 ## [3,] 7 8 9 diag(A) # Extract diagonal elements ## [1] 1 5 9 sum(diag(A)) # Trace of A: 1 + 5 + 9 = 15 ## [1] 15 7.11 Determinant The determinant tells us whether a matrix is invertible. A matrix is invertible if and only if its determinant is non-zero: A &lt;- matrix(c(2, 1, 5, 3), nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE) A ## [,1] [,2] ## [1,] 2 1 ## [2,] 5 3 det(A) # Determinant of A ## [1] 1 7.12 Matrix Inverse If \(\det(A) 
eq 0\), the inverse \(A^{-1}\) exists. Use solve() to compute it: A &lt;- matrix(c(2, 1, 5, 3), nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE) det(A) # Confirm it&#39;s invertible (non-zero) ## [1] 1 solve(A) # Inverse of A ## [,1] [,2] ## [1,] 3 -1 ## [2,] -5 2 # Verify: A %*% A^{-1} should equal the identity matrix round(A %*% solve(A), 10) ## [,1] [,2] ## [1,] 1 0 ## [2,] 0 1 7.13 Solving a System of Linear Equations solve(A, b) solves the system \(A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}\) for \(\mathbf{x}\). This is more numerically stable than computing solve(A) %*% b explicitly: # System: 2x1 + x2 = 8 # 5x1 + 3x2 = 19 A &lt;- matrix(c(2, 1, 5, 3), nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE) b &lt;- c(8, 19) x_star &lt;- solve(A, b) cat(&quot;x1 =&quot;, x_star[1], &quot;
&quot;) ## x1 = 5 cat(&quot;x2 =&quot;, x_star[2], &quot;
&quot;) ## x2 = -2 # Verify the solution A %*% x_star # Should return c(8, 19) ## [,1] ## [1,] 8 ## [2,] 19 7.14 Eigenvalues and Eigenvectors A &lt;- matrix(c(4, 1, 2, 3), nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE) eig &lt;- eigen(A) eig$values # Eigenvalues ## [1] 5 2 eig$vectors # Eigenvectors (columns) ## [,1] [,2] ## [1,] 0.7071068 -0.4472136 ## [2,] 0.7071068 0.8944272
